# Known test262 failures for the default (non-generated) conformance run,
# consumed by test/test262_runner.mjs. Each line is a test path (relative to
# the test262 checkout root); text after the path is an ignored comment.
#
# The runner exits nonzero on any UNEXPECTED failure OR any UNEXPECTED pass,
# so this list can only shrink silently: fix a gap and its test starts
# passing, which fails the run until the line is removed here. Every entry
# below is a real, understood gap or an out-of-scope concern -- not a
# rubber stamp. docs/CONFORMANCE_GAPS.md is the human-facing work-through
# list (what each gap is, why, and how to fix it); this file is the exact
# machine-checked set. Keep them in sync -- fixing a gap means deleting its
# line HERE and its entry THERE.
#
# Pinned test262 commit: see TEST262_SHA in scripts/get_test262.sh. Bumping
# it may add/remove tests; re-triage this file when you do.

## Out of scope: match-RESULT-OBJECT plumbing, not engine behavior.
# These assert the property descriptors (writable/enumerable/configurable)
# and prototype of the Array that String.prototype.match / RegExp.exec
# return. This engine's job ends at producing capture spans; assembling
# them into a spec-shaped RegExp result object is the host's RegExp
# implementation, which a standalone matcher doesn't own. The runner's shim
# builds a plausible result array but does not replicate every descriptor.
test/built-ins/RegExp/match-indices/indices-groups-object.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/match-indices/indices-property.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/named-groups/groups-object.js

## Real gap: Unicode case-insensitive matching of BUILT-IN class escapes
# and word boundaries. Under /iu, \w \W \p \P \b \B must fold via simple
# case folding (e.g. U+017F LONG S folds to 's', so /\w/iu matches it, and
# /\W/iu must not). This engine already folds *explicit* [...] classes
# (apply_case_folding), but not the built-in escapes. It's all-or-nothing:
# folding \w without \W would let one char match both, so the fix also
# needs \W/\D/\S represented as a negated positive set (they're currently
# pre-complemented) and is_word_char made fold-aware. Self-contained
# correctness project, tracked separately.
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-lower-b.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-lower-p.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-lower-w.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-upper-b.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-upper-p.js
test/built-ins/RegExp/regexp-modifiers/add-ignoreCase-affects-slash-upper-w.js

## Real gap: a \p{...} property escape used as a character-class RANGE
# endpoint (e.g. [\p{Hex}--] under /u) must be an early SyntaxError. This
# engine's range-endpoint rejection covers \d\w\s but not \p{...}. Narrow
# parser fix, deferred to avoid disturbing the passing class-range tests.
test/built-ins/RegExp/property-escapes/character-class-range-start.js

# NOTE: `node test/test262_runner.mjs --generated` additionally runs the
# machine-generated exhaustive sweeps under */generated/, which surface two
# further known gaps not enumerated line-by-line here: /v-mode set
# operations ([a&&b] intersection, [a--b] difference -- an unimplemented
# ES2024 feature) and RGI_Emoji multi-codepoint sequences beyond the
# 128-per-class cap (documented in docs/IMPROVEMENTS.md "Fixed since this
# analysis"). CI runs the default (non-generated) scope.
